<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-11-08T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-11-08T00:00:00-05:00" n="1204" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1204">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/5441.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Consul at C. P.
                                    Diaz</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi>.</head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Consulate</hi>, <hi rend="italic">Ciudad Porfirio Diaz.</hi>
                                </placeName>
                                <lb/> [<date ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-document-content-and-sibling-dates" calendar="gregorian" when="1912-11-08">undated</date>] (Received
                                November 8, 1912—6.10 p.m.)</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>About 1,000 rebels in the southern part of this district, in bands of 50
                            or less. Impossible to say who leads them. In the northern part, about
                            1,000 have operated during the past month, but are supposed to have
                            crossed into Chihuahua.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Luther T. Ellsworth.</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>